  "ai_overview": {
    "text_blocks": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "snippet": "The Electoral College is the official system used in the United States to elect the president and vice president every four years. It was established by the U.S. Constitution as a compromise between allowing citizens to vote directly for the president and allowing Congress to make the choice.",
        "snippet_links": [
          {
            "link": "https://www.archives.gov/electoral-college/about"
          }
        ],
        "reference_indexes": [
          0,
          1,
          4,
          5
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "snippet": "The system operates through a group of representatives called electors. Every state is assigned a specific number of electors equal to its total representation in Congress: two for its senators, plus a variable number based on its representatives in the House. The more populous a state, the more electors it has.",
        "snippet_links": [
          {
            "link": "https://www.archives.gov/electoral-college/about"
          }
        ],
        "reference_indexes": [
          0,
          1,
          2
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "snippet": "Here are a few key details about how it works:"
      },
      {
        "type": "list",
        "list": [
          {
            "snippet": "The Electors: There are 538 total electors in the Electoral College, which includes three representing Washington, D.C."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "snippet": "After citizens cast their ballots in November, the electors meet in mid-December to officially cast their votes for president and vice president. Congress then counts these votes in early January to finalize the election results.",
        "snippet_links": [
          {
            "link": "https://www.usa.gov/electoral-college"
          }
        ],
        "reference_indexes": [
          2,
          4
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "snippet": "You can find more detailed information and the specific allocation of electoral votes for each state on the USAGov and National Archives websites.",
        "snippet_links": [
          {
            "text": "USAGov",
            "link": "https://www.usa.gov/electoral-college"
          },
          {
            "text": "National Archives",
            "link": "https://www.archives.gov/electoral-college/about"
          }
        ],
        "reference_indexes": [
          6,
          7,
          8
        ]
      }
    ],
